<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-462-576  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 462 576.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>M.D. Computing  May-June 1989 v6 n3 p141(8).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Role of computing in patient care in two hospitals. (Beth IsraelHospital and Brigham and Women's Hospital)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Safran, Charles; Slack, Warner V.; Bleich, Howard L.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Two Boston hospitals, Beth Israel and Brigham and Women's, haveinstalled hospital-wide clinical computing systems.andP;  The systemshelp physicians, nurses, medical students, and other personnel incaring for patients.andP;  Video-display terminals throughout thehospital display the results from the clinical laboratories, thediagnostic reports from the clinical departments, the lists ofmedications used during hospitalization and prescriptions filledin the outpatient pharmacy, patients' charts, and databaseinformation.andP;  The terminals are also used for electronic mail.andO;The intensive use of the systems by physicians suggests that areliable, comprehensive, and easy-to-use computer system cansubstantially contribute to the quality of patient care.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Beth Israel HospitalBrigham and Women's HospitalHospital Information SystemsMedical Advice SystemsHealth CareIntegrated Systems.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   (Sample screen reports). (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>